policies.health_coverage: New Health Insurance Marketplace Coverage Options and Your Health Coverage
policies.gen_info_data: When key parts of the health care law take effect in 2014, there will be a new way to buy health insurance: the Health Insurance Marketplace ("Marketplace"). To assist you as you evaluate options for you and your family, this notice provides some basic information about the new Marketplace and employment based health coverage offered by your employer.
policies.health_insurance: What is the Health Insurance Marketplace?
policies.health_data: The Marketplace is designed to help you find health insurance that meets your needs and fits your budget. The Marketplace offers "one-stop shopping" to find and compare private health insurance options. You may also be eligible for a new kind of tax credit that lowers your monthly premium right away. Open enrollment for health insurance coverage through the Marketplace begins in October 2013 for coverage starting as early as January 1, 2014.
policies.save_money: Can I Save Money on my Health Insurance Premiums in the Marketplace?
policies.money_data: You may qualify to save money and lower your monthly premium, but only if your employer does not offer coverage, or offers coverage that doesn't meet certain standards. The savings on your premium that you're eligible for depends on your household income.
policies.cover_elgible: Does Employer Health Coverage Affect Eligibility for Premium Savings through the Marketplace?
policies.elgible_data: Yes. If you have an offer of health coverage from your employer that meets certain standards, you will not be eligible for a tax credit through the Marketplace and may wish to enroll in your employer's health plan. However, you may be eligible for a tax credit that lowers your monthly premium or a reduction in certain cost-sharing if your employer does not offer coverage to you at all or does not offer coverage that meets certain standards. If the cost of a plan from your employer that would cover you (and not any other members of your family) is more than 9.5% of your household income for the year, or if the coverage your employer provides does not meet the "minimum value" standard set by the Affordable Care Act, you may be eligible for a tax credit.1
policies.eligible_ndata: If you purchase a health plan through the Marketplace instead of accepting health coverage offered by your employer, then you may lose the employer contribution (if any) to the employer-offered coverage. Also, this employer contribution -as well as your employee contribution to employer-offered coverage- is often excluded from income for Federal and State income tax purposes. Your payments for coverage through the Marketplace are made on an after- tax basis.

policies.protect_act: Newborns' and Mothers' Health Protection Act
policies.act_datafrst: On September 26, 1996, a Federal law known as the Newborns' and Mothers' Health Protection Act of 1996 ("Newborns' Act") was enacted to include new protections for mothers and their newborn children with regard to the length of the hospital stay following childbirth. This notice is intended to inform you, in a summary fashion, of your rights under the law.
policies.act_datascnd: Group health plans and health insurance issuers generally may not, under federal law, restrict benefits for any hospital length of stay in connection with childbirth for the mother or newborn childto less than 48 hours following a vaginal delivery, or less than 96 hours following a cesarean section.
policies.act_datathrd: However, federal law generally does not prohibit the mother's or newborn's attending provider, after consulting with the mother, from discharging the mother or her newborn earlier than 48 hours (or 96 hours as applicable.)
policies.act_datafrth: In any case, plans and issuers may not, under federal law, require that a provider obtain authorization from the plan or the issuer for prescribing a length of stay not in excess of 48 hours (or 96 hours.)
policies.act_datafifth: If your state has a law that provides similar hospital stay protections and your plan offers coverage through an insurance policy or HMO, then you may be protected under state law rather than the Newborns' and Mothers' Health Protection Act
policies.right_women: Notification of Rights under the Women's Health and Cancer Rights Act
policies.womenone: On October 21, 1998, a Federal law (H.R. 4328) known as the Women's Health and Cancer Rights Act of 1998 ("Women's Health Act") was enacted requiring group health plans and insurance companies that provide coverage for mastectomies to provide certain mastectomy-related benefits or services to plan participants or beneficiaries. This notice is intended to inform you, in a summary fashion, of your rights under the law.
policies.womenscnd: Under the law, a group health plan participant or beneficiary who is receiving benefits in connection with a mastectomy, and who elects breast reconstruction in connection with the mastectomy, is entitled to coverage for the following
policies.wmn_top: 1. Reconstruction of the breast on which the mastectomy has been performed
policies.wmn_midl: 2. Surgery and reconstruction of the other breast to produce a symmetrical appearance and
policies.wmn_bottom: 3. Prostheses and treatment of physical complications at all stages of mastectomy, including lymphedemas.
policies.wmn_servce: Coverage for these benefits or services will be provided in a manner determined in consultation with the participant's or beneficiary's attending physician.
policies.wmn_subs: If you are a covered member or qualified dependent under the TriNet Group, Inc., and Its Subsidiaries Medical Plan #501, and are currently receiving, or in the future receive, benefits under the plan in connection with a mastectomy, you are entitled to coverage for the benefits and services described above in the event that you elect breast reconstruction. Your qualified dependents are also entitled to coverage for those benefits or services on the same terms.
policies.wmn_mastec: Coverage for the mastectomy-related services or benefits required under the Women's Health Law will be subject to the same deductibles and coinsurance or co-payment provisions that apply with respect to other medical or surgical benefits provided under the TriNet Group, Inc., and Its Subsidiaries Medical Plan #501.

policies.overview_stmt1: TriNet is the single employer sponsor of all its benefit plans. TriNet makes these plans available to qualifying worksite employees ("WSEs"), with whom TriNet has established an employment relationship, and who perform services for customers of TriNet in a Professional Employer Organization ("PEO") service model. Please refer to the TriNet Benefits Guidebook for further details regarding benefits eligibility.
policies.overview_stmt2: It is very important that you waive or elect those benefits that best suit the needs of your family. If you do not make a benefits election during your 30-day election period, TriNet will automatically enroll you in employee only default medical coverage, which is generally the lowest cost PPO medical plan available in your geographic area. The default medical coverage in which you automatically are enrolled because you failed to make a timely benefits election may not be the coverage you want. If you already have group medical coverage, you may choose to waive or opt out of TriNet's medical benefits.
policies.overview_stmt3: TriNet partners with leading carriers, like Aetna, Florida Blue, Blue Shield of California and Kaiser, to offer a broad range of medical plans, including high-deductible health plans, PPOs and HMOs. Medical plan options vary by state, and may also include regional carriers.

policies.overview_stmt9: The Company provides a policy that may replace up to 66.67% of your salary, up to a maximum benefit of $2,308 per week, for qualifying disabilities, for up to a maximum benefit of 180 days.

policies.overview_stmt11: TriNet also offers a high and a low vision plan nationally through two different carriers: Aetna and Vision Service Plan (VSP). These plan options ensure that you can choose the best plan and carrier for your individual vision needs.
policies.overview_stmt12: FSAs help you pay for eligible out-of-pocket health care and dependent day care expenses on a pre-tax basis. Spousal coverage is also available in increments of $10,000 up to $150,000, and child coverage for $10,000. policies.overview_stmt15: Disability insurance plans are designed to provide income protection while you recover from a disability. home.title: Home
home.heading: Flexible Spending Account (FSA) Plan Calculator
home.para1: Flexible spending accounts (FSAs) help you pay for eligible out-of-pocket health and dependent day care expenses on a pre-tax basis. To help you evaluate your choices and make the elections that are right for you and your family, we offer a set of online decision tools.
home.li1: A health care FSA calculator, to help you estimate your out-of-pocket medical, dental and vision costs, and potential federal tax savings.
home.li2: A health care FSA calculator, to help you estimate your out-of-pocket medical, dental and vision costs, and potential federal tax savings.
home.para2: Important notice if you are a shareholder or partner: If you are considered self-employed under Internal Revenue Code (IRC) Section 401(c), you are not eligible to participate in TriNet health care or dependent day care FSA. You may be considered self-employed for purposes of the Plan even if you are paid wages through TriNet payroll. If you are a shareholder or partner, we recommend that you consult your tax attorney or advisor before you elect to participate in a TriNet health care or dependent day care FSA.

about.title: About FSA
about.para1: The FSA calculators are designed to help you decide whether to participate in the TriNet health care and/or dependent day care flexible spending accounts.
about.para2: Estimate your eligible health care costs during the TriNet plan year, and then use the health care FSA calculator to help you estimate your annual health care FSA election. The dependent day care FSA calculator helps you make the same decision about electing an FSA to pay your eligible dependent day care expenses.
about.para3: Both FSA calculators also can help you estimate federal tax savings; state and local income taxes are not taken into account.
about.para4: As you consider the FSA calculator results, keep in mind that if you do not timely submit a claim for reimbursement prior to the claim submission deadline you will forfeit or lose any money you do not use that is left in your FSAs at the end of the plan year or when your FSA participation ends, whichever is earlier. So, it is important to carefully estimate your expenses for the plan year before electing your FSA contributions.
about.para5: Disclaimer: Any information you enter into the calculators is not available to your worksite, TriNet, TriNet employees, or insurance carriers. This includes any tax information you enter to calculate your savings.

dc.title: Dependent Care
dc.para1: The dependent day care FSA helps you pay for eligible out-of-pocket dependent day care expenses on a pre-tax basis. Generally, you can be reimbursed for qualified dependent day care expenses such as child care for children under the age of 13 or anyone who you claim as a dependent on your federal tax return who is physically or mentally incapable of self-care, so that you (and your spouse, if you are married) can work, look for work, or attend school full time.
dc.para2: The dependent day care FSA calculator is designed to help you decide whether to participate in a TriNet dependent day care FSA by estimating your out-of-pocket expenses and potential tax savings. As you consider the FSA calculator results, keep in mind that if you do not timely submit a claim for reimbursement prior to the claim submission deadline, you will forfeit any money that is left in your FSA at the end of the plan year. It is important to carefully estimate your expenses before electing to participate in a TriNet FSA. Also be aware that you may be eligible to take advantage of the federal tax credit for child and dependent day care as an alternative to using the dependent day care FSA. You may wish to consult a tax advisor to determine whether the federal tax credit or dependent day care FSA is best for you.
dc.para3: Important notice if you are a shareholder or partner: If you are self-employed under Internal Revenue Code Section 401(c), you are not eligible to participate in a TriNet FSA. You may be considered self-employed for purposes of the Plan even if you are paid as a worksite employee through TriNet payroll. If you are a shareholder or partner, we recommend that you consult your tax attorney or advisor before you elect to participate in an FSA.

hc.title: Health Care
hc.para1: The health care FSA helps you pay for eligible out­of­pocket healthcare expenses on a pre­tax basis. Generally, you can be reimbursed for services or supplies needed to prevent or treat an illness or medical condition if the expense is not reimbursed by your own or a spouse’s health care plan. Any expense incurred strictly for cosmetic reasons is not eligible. Insurance premiums, including those for long­term care insurance or COBRA, are also ineligible expenses.
hc.para2: The health care FSA calculator can help you estimate your out­of­pocket healthcare expenses, and potential federal tax savings, if you use this pre­tax account to pay for eligible healthcare expenses. Only estimate expenses for your IRS defined tax dependents. FSA benefits only extend to domestic partners and domestic partner children if these individuals qualify as your federal tax dependent(s). Adult children who have attained age 26 are not tax dependents unless they are disabled.
hc.para3: If you are electing both an HSA and FSA, or your worksite contributes to your HSA, your participation in the health care FSA is limited to out­of­pocket dental and vision expenses. Budget for your medical expenses through your HSA.

You may be considered self­employed for purposes of the Plan, even if you are paid wages through TriNet payroll. measurementStabilityPeriod.heading: ACA measurement and stability period.
measurementStabilityPeriod.employerSharedResponsibility: To comply with the ACA Employer Shared Responsibility provision, Applicable Large Employers (ALEs) will need to offer coverage to 95% of full-time employees and FTEs to avoid having to pay penalties. We recommend you classify all worksite employees (WSEs) who are working or expected to work 30 or more hours per week as full-time, eligible for benefits. When you enter your worksite employees in the TriNet system, please make sure to classify them correctly.
measurementStabilityPeriod.contactAssistanceUpdate: Contact your Human Capital Consultant or Client Services Associate if you require assistance updating your worksite employee classifications.
measurementStabilityPeriod.variableHourEmployee: If you cannot determine at the date of hire if a worksite employee is expected to work at least 30 hours per week, that employee is a variable-hour employee. We offer a monthly reporting service that will help you identify which variable-hour employees should be treated as "full-time" and thus benefits eligible by:
measurementStabilityPeriod.measurementPeriod: Calculating average weekly hours worked during a specified period of months (12 months), which is referred to as a Measurement Period. Your company will begin receiving monthly reports that track average hours for your employees.
measurementStabilityPeriod.stabilityPeriod: Locking in the worksite employees' status ("full-time" benefits eligible or benefits ineligible) during a subsequent specified period of months (following the Measurement Period), which is referred to as the Stability Period. The WSE's status is based on the calculation from the Measurement Period and is locked in for the entire duration of the Stability Period.
measurementStabilityPeriod.administrativePeriod: We will use 12 months of employment data to track average hours. There will be a one-month Administrative Period, between the end of the Measurement Period and the start of the Stability Period. If you have any questions regarding the Measurement Period and the Stability Period, please contact your Human Capital Consultant.
measurementStabilityPeriod.submitInfoOne: We offer 12-month Measurement and Stability Periods. The length of the Measurement and Stability Periods will be the same for new and ongoing WSEs.
measurementStabilityPeriod.submitInfoTwo: By submitting this certification, you attest that you have been advised to consult with a tax and/or legal advisor and have carefully reviewed the Affordable Care Act (ACA) rules and regulations regarding the Employer Shared Responsibility provisions under Section 4980H of the Internal Revenue Code and the applicable Treasury Regulations thereunder. If the IRS informs your company of potential liability for a Section 4980H tax penalty assessment under ACA Employer Shared Responsibility, your company shall be solely responsible for responding to such notice and for paying any Code Section 4980H penalties that may be assessed.
measurementStabilityPeriod.submitInfoThree: You will have an opportunity to submit a new ALE designation prior to the start of each calendar year. However, your company's designation as a non-ALE will remain in effect during future calendar years unless and until an authorized representative submits a new certification for a subsequent calendar year.
